Replays the type-append logic that Pass B would enumerate, but driven by an obligation stack rather than a precomputed table: appending an N-arity type pushes N argument obligations, and each subsequent type stroke discharges the innermost. No rows are enumerated; cost is proportional to pressed strokes and nesting is unbounded.

The walker's core invariant: `walk(strokes, types, constructs) -> Option<WalkResult>` matches the stroke sequence against construct bases (scoring by specificity: longer/fused constructs score higher), then fills their slots in D12 order by consuming complete nested types from the residual strokes. Returns `None` if any stroke is not a valid type, if extra strokes remain after all slots are filled, or if no construct matches — never panics on user input. `WalkResult.terminal` is true iff every slot is filled and no obligation remains.

`consume_type(ts, pos, types)` recursively parses a complete (possibly nested) type starting at `*pos`, advancing the position. Returns `Consumed` with the rendered text and a `complete` flag; `complete = false` when strokes run out mid-obligation, producing a bracketless partial form ("Array" or "Map number"). `render_type(text, args)` substitutes args into `%t` markers (the wire format passed from construct and type definitions). The template rendering (`template_fragments`, `render_filled`) splits at slots to interleave type texts in D12 order — this exact representation mirrors what `build-javelin`'s C++ replay emits, so output is identical by construction.